import Foundation

enum MotivationLibrary {
    static let all: [ContentEntry] = [
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-01", text: "Hoping a health problem fades on its own is not a plan. You are the one who can choose the next meal, the next walk, the next bedtime—and those choices are how problems actually start to change."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-02", text: "No one else can care about your body for you. If you do not take ownership of sleep, food, and movement, the cost shows up in your energy and in how you show up for the people you love."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-03", text: "Wishful thinking does not lower risk or build stamina. What moves the needle is steady action: small decisions you repeat until they become the foundation you and your relationships can rely on."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-04", text: "Your health is not a lottery ticket. It reflects what you are willing to prioritize and protect. Choosing to invest in yourself is choosing to be more present and less drained for others."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-05", text: "Problems that matter rarely vanish because we ignore them. They improve when we face them with honest effort—when you decide that your well-being and your relationships are worth the discomfort of change."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-06", text: "Blame and regret do not build a better week. Responsibility does: owning what you can control today, even when yesterday was hard, and making one clear move toward health instead of waiting for a perfect moment."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-07", text: "You cannot outsource self-respect. Caring for your health is how you signal—to yourself and to people close to you—that you intend to be here, capable, and engaged for the long run."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-08", text: "Hope without action is thin. When you pair hope with real changes—earlier sleep, more plants, consistent movement—you give yourself and your relationships something solid to build on."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-09", text: "Avoiding the issue does not protect your family or friends; it often makes you less patient and less available. Taking responsibility for your health is a practical way to show up with more steadiness and care."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-10", text: "The path forward is not magic. It is a series of choices that say: I will not passively accept decline. I will do what I can, starting now, because my life and my connections matter enough to try."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-11", text: "You do not need permission to prioritize basics. Sleep, nutrition, and exercise are not selfish hobbies—they are how you keep promises to yourself and have bandwidth for people who depend on you."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-12", text: "If you want different outcomes, something has to change—and that something includes your habits, not only your hopes. Personal responsibility means choosing the harder right option more often than the easy drift."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-13", text: "Relationships thrive when people are regulated enough to listen and repair. That regulation is partly biological: when you steward your health, you give yourself a fairer chance to be the partner, parent, or friend you want to be."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-14", text: "Passivity is still a choice. Deciding to take one concrete step—book the walk, cook the simple meal, set a firm lights-out time—is how you break the trance of “maybe it will get better on its own.”"),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-15", text: "You are allowed to start small, but not to pretend you have no role. Every day you either reinforce old patterns or practice new ones. Own the direction you are rehearsing."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-16", text: "Resentment often grows when we feel powerless. Reclaiming agency over your health—even imperfectly—can soften that edge and free attention for connection instead of survival mode."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-17", text: "Denial buys short-term comfort and long-term cost. Facing where you are and choosing the next right step is an act of courage—and a form of love for your future self and the people who share your life."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-18", text: "Sustainable improvement is not about shame; it is about stewardship. You are responsible for tending the one body you have and for not expecting others to carry what only you can change."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-19", text: "When you treat your health as negotiable, everything downstream becomes harder—work, mood, intimacy, patience. When you treat it as non-negotiable enough to act on, you create room for real repair and growth."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-20", text: "The story that “it should be easier” keeps people stuck. What sets you free is deciding that your well-being and your relationships are worth the effort—then proving it with repeated choices, not just good intentions."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-21", text: "Good energy and steady confidence are not accidents—they are outcomes you train. If you want to feel capable in your skin and clear in your relationships, you must own sleep, food, and movement."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-22", text: "DBT’s wise mind joins feeling and fact: you may want comfort now and vitality later. Choose the action that honors both—discipline is integrating truth, not punishing yourself."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-23", text: "Distress tolerance means you can feel an urge—to scroll, snack, stay up—and still choose differently. Each tolerated discomfort is proof you are responsible for your health, not a victim of mood."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-24", text: "Delaying gratification builds the life you say you want. Ten minutes of vegetable prep or a walk you do not “feel like” is how you earn tomorrow’s patience with people you care about."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-25", text: "Opposite action: when your mind says skip the walk or raid the pantry, move toward your values instead. Responsibility is behaving like the person you intend to be before feelings cooperate."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-26", text: "Radical acceptance: this is your body today. From here, one effective choice—earlier lights-out, fiber at lunch—creates momentum. Waiting for perfect motivation is avoidance dressed as hope."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-27", text: "Behavioral activation beats rumination: act first, let mood catch up. Your confidence grows from evidence that you keep promises to yourself about health—even when it is inconvenient."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-28", text: "Healthy relationships require a regulated you. Sleep deprivation and erratic fuel make irritability and withdrawal more likely. Caring for yourself is caring for the quality of your connections."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-29", text: "You are responsible for the tradeoffs you make. Short-term ease often purchases long-term fragility; short-term discipline purchases energy, self-trust, and the ability to love people without running on fumes."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-30", text: "Emotion regulation is a skill set, not a trait. Sleep, whole-food fiber, and exercise minutes are daily practice in managing your inner state—so you can bring patience, clarity, and presence to every relationship you value."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-31", text: "Meet people where they are—it is the only place real change ever begins, theirs or yours. Drop today's score-keeping. Notice the person in front of you with patience, then notice yourself with the same grace."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-32", text: "Acceptance is not approval and it is not surrender. You can love someone exactly as they are today and still want, fiercely, for them to flourish tomorrow. Hold that same posture toward yourself: meet today honestly, then choose the next small step."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-33", text: "A growth mindset means feedback is information, not an insult. When someone names something hard about you, breathe before defending. They are offering you a door—walk through it."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-34", text: "Wanting good things for someone is not pressure—it is love refusing to settle for less than their full life. Apply that same love to your own sleep, fiber, and movement today."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-35", text: "If your identity rests on always being right, every comment becomes a threat. If your identity rests on always growing, every comment becomes a gift. Choose the second posture and watch your relationships open up."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-36", text: "You cannot shame anyone—yourself included—into lasting change. Acceptance opens the door; love walks through it. Take one small step today because you are worth steady care, not because you are not enough."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-37", text: "The people who grow the fastest are the ones who lean toward hard conversations, not away from them. Sit with the discomfort. Ask one more question. You are safe enough to be a learner."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-38", text: "Love that is afraid to say the true thing is not love—it is conflict avoidance dressed in kindness. Speak gently, honestly, and with hope for the other person's growth. Then turn that same honesty inward on the choice in front of you tonight."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-39", text: "When you see yourself as a work in progress, tonight's sleep is not a chore—it is one more chapter. Fiber today is not a punishment—it is care. The way you treat yourself teaches the people who love you how to treat themselves."),
        ContentEntry(id: "mot-40", text: "Being open to feedback is not weakness—it is the quiet strength of someone who knows they are still becoming. Welcome the hard input. Then go to bed on time anyway. Growth shows up in both places."),
    ]
}
